04074nam a22006375i 9780814725030DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19961996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147250307 a10.18574/97808147250302doi  a(DE-B1597)550559  a(OCoLC)784884453  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDJK51b.B867 1996 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a320.94/09171/72201 aBurg, Stephen L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar or Peace? :bNationalism, Democracy, and American Foreign Policy in Post- Communist Europe /cStephen L. Burg. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTABLES AND MAPS -- tFOREWORD -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER 1. Nationalism, Democracy, and International Peace in Post-Communist Europe -- tCHAPTER 2. Ethnic Conflict and the Euro-Atlantic Community: The Yugoslav Crisis -- tCHAPTER 3. From Nationalism to Democratization -- tCHAPTER 4. Conclusion: Toward an American Strategy for Peace -- tNOTES -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than forty years, Western policymakers defined communism as the central threat to international peace and stability. They responded by confronting it with a counterbalancing threat of force, and pursuing a strategy of containment. With the collapse of communism, the challenge to peace and stability in the Euro-Atlantic community has changed. Soviet expansionism has been supplanted by powerful, internal forces arising out of the clash of competing ethnic nationalisms. This challenge, argues Steven L. Burg, cannot be met by force alone, or neutralized through a strategy of containment. It requires Western states to act decisively to influence the internal political development of the post- communist states themselves. Burg surveys the challenges that the ethnic diversity in Eastern Europe present to domestic stability, international peace, and American interests, and suggests policies and practices by which the United States and its allies might contribute to the consolidation of peace in the region. He provides a concise explanation and analysis of the issues, evaluates the usefulness of scholarly approaches to the resolution of ethnic conflicts, and offers a strategy of what he calls preventive engagement by which policymakers may prevent conflicts such as the one that destroyed the former Yugoslavia. War or Peace? offers clear and direct recommendations to guide both interested citizens and national policymakers as they attempt to grapple with the complexities of ethnic and nationalist politics in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDemocracy. 0aNationalismzEurope, Eastern. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814725030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814725030.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK